{"actor":{"type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":"1\t# Technical design\n2\t\n3\t**Status:** implemented in v0.1; format may still evolve until v1.\n4\t\n5\t## Scope\n6\t\n7\tConversation Ledger defines a canonical append-only event format plus a local,\n8\tgit-backed storage protocol. It preserves exact visible content while staying\n9\tout of the working tree and syncing only on explicit request.\n10\t\n11\t## Canonical objects\n12\t\n13\tAn `EvidenceEvent` is immutable and has:\n14\t\n15\t- `id`: `ev1-` + sha256 of the event's *identity subset* — the durable,\n16\t  source-determined fields (`kind`, `occurred_at`, `actor.type/id`,\n17\t  `producer.source/session_id`, `conversation`, `media_type`, `content`,\n18\t  `links`). Volatile provenance (`recorded_at`, `context`, `raw`,\n19\t  `producer.tool/version`) is excluded, so re-scanning the same source\n20\t  material always yields the same id: capture is idempotent by construction,\n21\t  and the id doubles as the content hash that makes mutation detectable.\n22\t- `schema` version (`conversation-ledger/v1`);\n23\t- `kind`: `conversation_turn`, `decision`, `document`, `annotation`,\n24\t  `redaction`, or `supersession` — an open string; unknown kinds are stored\n25\t  verbatim so downstream tools can extend without a schema release;\n26\t- `occurred_at` (from the source) and `recorded_at` (at append) timestamps;\n27\t- `actor` (human/agent/system + identity) and `producer` (capture tool,\n28\t  source system, native session id) provenance; adapters stamp human turns\n29\t  with the repo's `git config user.email`/`user.name` (`actor.id`/`.display`)\n30\t  so multi-user clients can filter by author. Because `actor.id` is part of\n31\t  the event identity subset, sessions captured before this stamping existed\n32\t  will produce new event ids if fully re-scanned — the per-session cursor\n33\t  normally prevents that, but a forced rescan can duplicate pre-identity\n34\t  turns;\n35\t- `content`, stored inline, with an optional `media_type`\n36\t  (default `application/json`);\n37\t- `context`: repository identity, branch, `HEAD` SHA, cwd, and a\n38\t  dirty-worktree fingerprint (sha256 of `git status --porcelain`);\n39\t- `conversation`: namespaced id (`claude-code:<session>`) plus a stable\n40\t  `seq` (source line index) providing conversation ordering — the manifest is\n41\t  currently implicit in these fields rather than a separate object;\n42\t- optional `links` (`redacts`, `supersedes`, `annotates`, ...).\n43\t\n44\tConversation turns preserve visible roles, text, tool calls, and tool results\n45\tas supplied by their capture adapter. The source-native payload is retained\n46\tunder `raw` as an opaque, versioned attachment for lossless export.\n47\t\n48\tReasoning policy: record model reasoning when the provider exposes it\n49\t(Claude Code's thinking text is kept, minus opaque signatures); never chase\n50\tit when the provider withholds it (Codex's encrypted `reasoning` payloads\n51\tare skipped, not stored, and never reconstructed).\n52\t\n53\t## Storage\n54\t\n55\tOne git note per **anchor commit** under `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`.\n56\tThe note body is JSONL: one canonical-JSON (sorted-keys) event per line,\n57\tlexicographically sorted, unique.\n58\t\n59\tWhy this shape:\n60\t\n61\t1. **Branch-tied by construction.** Events anchor to `HEAD` at capture time,\n62\t   so conversations ride the commit DAG: merging a branch makes its commits —\n63\t   and therefore their conversations — reachable from the target branch with\n64\t   no sync machinery. `cledger log` scopes to the current branch via\n65\t   `git rev-list` reachability.\n66\t2. **GC-safe, nothing outside git.** All content lives inline in the note\n67\t   blob, reachable from the ref. No orphan data branches, no pointers to\n68\t   stores outside the repository.\n69\t3. **Conflict-free concurrency.** Deterministic serialization + sorted unique\n70\t   lines mean git's `cat_sort_uniq` notes merge strategy (configured per-ref\n71\t   at first append) unions concurrent appends cleanly — the same mechanism\n72\t   git-bug and git-appraise rely on.\n73\t4. **Clean working tree.** Notes never appear in `git status`; sharing is an\n74\t   explicit `cledger sync` (fetch → `git notes merge -s cat_sort_uniq` →\n75\t   push) of that single ref, never implicit.\n76\t\n77\tEvents captured before the first commit exists (unborn `HEAD`) queue in\n78\t`.git/conversation-ledger/pending.jsonl` and flush into the first real\n79\tanchor. Everything under `.git/conversation-ledger/` (pending queue, adapter\n80\tcursors, lock) is local, rebuildable state — never the record of truth.\n81\t\n82\t### Known limitation: squash merges\n83\t\n84\tA squash merge discards the source branch's commits, so their conversations\n85\tremain in the ledger (notes are enumerable regardless of reachability;\n86\t`cledger log --all` sees them) but drop out of the target branch's\n87\treachability view. A future `re-anchor` operation is the intended fix.\n88\t\n89\t## Capture adapters\n90\t\n91\t`cledger install` registers per-turn hooks globally: Claude Code\n92\t(`Stop`/`SessionEnd` in `~/.claude/settings.json`) and Codex CLI\n93\t(`[[hooks.Stop]]` in `~/.codex/config.toml`). Hooks receive\n94\t`session_id`/`transcript_path`/`cwd` on stdin, no-op silently outside git\n95\trepositories, never fail the user's session, and re-scan tolerantly —\n96\tidempotent ids make duplicate capture harmless. Per-session cursors under\n97\t`.git/conversation-ledger/cursors/` are a pure optimization.\n98\t\n99\t## Privacy and integrity\n100\t\n101\tVisible tool output can contain secrets. The ledger stays local until an\n102\texplicit `sync`; retention and remote-sharing policy belong to the repository\n103\towner. Redaction appends a `redaction` event linking to its target rather\n104\tthan pretending the original never existed; actually purging content is a\n105\tdeliberate, separate operation (planned) since note history retains prior\n106\tblobs. Content hashes (event ids) make accidental mutation detectable.\n107\t\n108\t## Versioning against harness format changes\n109\t\n110\tThree layers exist today:\n111\t\n112\t1. `schema` on every event (`conversation-ledger/v1`) versions the ledger's\n113\t   own envelope.\n114\t2. `raw.format` (`claude-code-jsonl/1`, `codex-rollout-jsonl/1`) versions\n115\t   each adapter's interpretation of its native format; it must be bumped\n116\t   whenever the mapping changes, allowing later reprocessing to know which\n117\t   parser produced an event.\n118\t3. The native payload inside `raw.data` retains the harness's own version\n119\t   markers (Claude Code lines carry `version`; Codex `session_meta` carries\n120\t   `cli_version`), so captured content can always be re-normalized under a\n121\t   newer mapping without recapture.\n122\t\n123\tWhat does not exist yet: drift detection. Adapters are tolerant parsers that\n124\tskip unrecognized line types, which handles additive upstream changes\n125\tgracefully but means a genuinely new message type is dropped entirely (raw\n126\tincluded — only converted lines are stored). See the format-drift roadmap\n127\titem.\n128\t\n129\t## Open questions\n130\t\n131\t- Secret-safety at capture time: automatic detection/redaction of API keys,\n132\t  tokens, and credentials in tool output before events are written (plus\n133\t  path/pattern-based exclusion rules). Tool output is the highest-risk\n134\t  content in the ledger and currently stored verbatim.\n135\t- Purge tooling for true content removal after redaction.\n136\t- Sub-turn citation anchors for downstream consumers (intent-recall).\n137\t- Re-anchoring after squash merges and history rewrites — ideally default\n138\t  behavior (squash commit inherits its branch's conversations), which\n139\t  requires detecting remote squashes (e.g. GitHub merges) via patch-id or\n140\t  branch-tip matching after fetch.\n141\t- Whether to preserve non-git-controlled harness artifacts that die with a\n142\t  worktree (agent memory directories, session state) as `document` events.\n143\t- Whether an explicit `Conversation` manifest object earns its keep once\n144\t  multiple producers exist.\n145\t","tool_use_id":"toolu_011stAACzzcp7DeiGs4h3tgF","type":"tool_result"}],"role":"user"},"context":{"branch":"main","cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","head":"c08f650fedfb44dd1e095b61aa2bd43ed5735597","repo":"git@github.com:evintunador/conversation-ledger.git"},"conversation":{"id":"claude-code:353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","seq":56},"id":"ev1-16101ddb7f357c727d4fe0ab7c619188ff177230b5586bdd6c3ad5c10b4788c2","kind":"conversation_turn","occurred_at":"2026-07-20T01:52:33.535Z","producer":{"session_id":"353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","source":"claude-code","tool":"cledger","version":"0.2.0"},"raw":{"data":{"cwd":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger","entrypoint":"cli","gitBranch":"main","isSidechain":false,"message":{"content":[{"content":"1\t# Technical design\n2\t\n3\t**Status:** implemented in v0.1; format may still evolve until v1.\n4\t\n5\t## Scope\n6\t\n7\tConversation Ledger defines a canonical append-only event format plus a local,\n8\tgit-backed storage protocol. It preserves exact visible content while staying\n9\tout of the working tree and syncing only on explicit request.\n10\t\n11\t## Canonical objects\n12\t\n13\tAn `EvidenceEvent` is immutable and has:\n14\t\n15\t- `id`: `ev1-` + sha256 of the event's *identity subset* — the durable,\n16\t  source-determined fields (`kind`, `occurred_at`, `actor.type/id`,\n17\t  `producer.source/session_id`, `conversation`, `media_type`, `content`,\n18\t  `links`). Volatile provenance (`recorded_at`, `context`, `raw`,\n19\t  `producer.tool/version`) is excluded, so re-scanning the same source\n20\t  material always yields the same id: capture is idempotent by construction,\n21\t  and the id doubles as the content hash that makes mutation detectable.\n22\t- `schema` version (`conversation-ledger/v1`);\n23\t- `kind`: `conversation_turn`, `decision`, `document`, `annotation`,\n24\t  `redaction`, or `supersession` — an open string; unknown kinds are stored\n25\t  verbatim so downstream tools can extend without a schema release;\n26\t- `occurred_at` (from the source) and `recorded_at` (at append) timestamps;\n27\t- `actor` (human/agent/system + identity) and `producer` (capture tool,\n28\t  source system, native session id) provenance; adapters stamp human turns\n29\t  with the repo's `git config user.email`/`user.name` (`actor.id`/`.display`)\n30\t  so multi-user clients can filter by author. Because `actor.id` is part of\n31\t  the event identity subset, sessions captured before this stamping existed\n32\t  will produce new event ids if fully re-scanned — the per-session cursor\n33\t  normally prevents that, but a forced rescan can duplicate pre-identity\n34\t  turns;\n35\t- `content`, stored inline, with an optional `media_type`\n36\t  (default `application/json`);\n37\t- `context`: repository identity, branch, `HEAD` SHA, cwd, and a\n38\t  dirty-worktree fingerprint (sha256 of `git status --porcelain`);\n39\t- `conversation`: namespaced id (`claude-code:<session>`) plus a stable\n40\t  `seq` (source line index) providing conversation ordering — the manifest is\n41\t  currently implicit in these fields rather than a separate object;\n42\t- optional `links` (`redacts`, `supersedes`, `annotates`, ...).\n43\t\n44\tConversation turns preserve visible roles, text, tool calls, and tool results\n45\tas supplied by their capture adapter. The source-native payload is retained\n46\tunder `raw` as an opaque, versioned attachment for lossless export.\n47\t\n48\tReasoning policy: record model reasoning when the provider exposes it\n49\t(Claude Code's thinking text is kept, minus opaque signatures); never chase\n50\tit when the provider withholds it (Codex's encrypted `reasoning` payloads\n51\tare skipped, not stored, and never reconstructed).\n52\t\n53\t## Storage\n54\t\n55\tOne git note per **anchor commit** under `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`.\n56\tThe note body is JSONL: one canonical-JSON (sorted-keys) event per line,\n57\tlexicographically sorted, unique.\n58\t\n59\tWhy this shape:\n60\t\n61\t1. **Branch-tied by construction.** Events anchor to `HEAD` at capture time,\n62\t   so conversations ride the commit DAG: merging a branch makes its commits —\n63\t   and therefore their conversations — reachable from the target branch with\n64\t   no sync machinery. `cledger log` scopes to the current branch via\n65\t   `git rev-list` reachability.\n66\t2. **GC-safe, nothing outside git.** All content lives inline in the note\n67\t   blob, reachable from the ref. No orphan data branches, no pointers to\n68\t   stores outside the repository.\n69\t3. **Conflict-free concurrency.** Deterministic serialization + sorted unique\n70\t   lines mean git's `cat_sort_uniq` notes merge strategy (configured per-ref\n71\t   at first append) unions concurrent appends cleanly — the same mechanism\n72\t   git-bug and git-appraise rely on.\n73\t4. **Clean working tree.** Notes never appear in `git status`; sharing is an\n74\t   explicit `cledger sync` (fetch → `git notes merge -s cat_sort_uniq` →\n75\t   push) of that single ref, never implicit.\n76\t\n77\tEvents captured before the first commit exists (unborn `HEAD`) queue in\n78\t`.git/conversation-ledger/pending.jsonl` and flush into the first real\n79\tanchor. Everything under `.git/conversation-ledger/` (pending queue, adapter\n80\tcursors, lock) is local, rebuildable state — never the record of truth.\n81\t\n82\t### Known limitation: squash merges\n83\t\n84\tA squash merge discards the source branch's commits, so their conversations\n85\tremain in the ledger (notes are enumerable regardless of reachability;\n86\t`cledger log --all` sees them) but drop out of the target branch's\n87\treachability view. A future `re-anchor` operation is the intended fix.\n88\t\n89\t## Capture adapters\n90\t\n91\t`cledger install` registers per-turn hooks globally: Claude Code\n92\t(`Stop`/`SessionEnd` in `~/.claude/settings.json`) and Codex CLI\n93\t(`[[hooks.Stop]]` in `~/.codex/config.toml`). Hooks receive\n94\t`session_id`/`transcript_path`/`cwd` on stdin, no-op silently outside git\n95\trepositories, never fail the user's session, and re-scan tolerantly —\n96\tidempotent ids make duplicate capture harmless. Per-session cursors under\n97\t`.git/conversation-ledger/cursors/` are a pure optimization.\n98\t\n99\t## Privacy and integrity\n100\t\n101\tVisible tool output can contain secrets. The ledger stays local until an\n102\texplicit `sync`; retention and remote-sharing policy belong to the repository\n103\towner. Redaction appends a `redaction` event linking to its target rather\n104\tthan pretending the original never existed; actually purging content is a\n105\tdeliberate, separate operation (planned) since note history retains prior\n106\tblobs. Content hashes (event ids) make accidental mutation detectable.\n107\t\n108\t## Versioning against harness format changes\n109\t\n110\tThree layers exist today:\n111\t\n112\t1. `schema` on every event (`conversation-ledger/v1`) versions the ledger's\n113\t   own envelope.\n114\t2. `raw.format` (`claude-code-jsonl/1`, `codex-rollout-jsonl/1`) versions\n115\t   each adapter's interpretation of its native format; it must be bumped\n116\t   whenever the mapping changes, allowing later reprocessing to know which\n117\t   parser produced an event.\n118\t3. The native payload inside `raw.data` retains the harness's own version\n119\t   markers (Claude Code lines carry `version`; Codex `session_meta` carries\n120\t   `cli_version`), so captured content can always be re-normalized under a\n121\t   newer mapping without recapture.\n122\t\n123\tWhat does not exist yet: drift detection. Adapters are tolerant parsers that\n124\tskip unrecognized line types, which handles additive upstream changes\n125\tgracefully but means a genuinely new message type is dropped entirely (raw\n126\tincluded — only converted lines are stored). See the format-drift roadmap\n127\titem.\n128\t\n129\t## Open questions\n130\t\n131\t- Secret-safety at capture time: automatic detection/redaction of API keys,\n132\t  tokens, and credentials in tool output before events are written (plus\n133\t  path/pattern-based exclusion rules). Tool output is the highest-risk\n134\t  content in the ledger and currently stored verbatim.\n135\t- Purge tooling for true content removal after redaction.\n136\t- Sub-turn citation anchors for downstream consumers (intent-recall).\n137\t- Re-anchoring after squash merges and history rewrites — ideally default\n138\t  behavior (squash commit inherits its branch's conversations), which\n139\t  requires detecting remote squashes (e.g. GitHub merges) via patch-id or\n140\t  branch-tip matching after fetch.\n141\t- Whether to preserve non-git-controlled harness artifacts that die with a\n142\t  worktree (agent memory directories, session state) as `document` events.\n143\t- Whether an explicit `Conversation` manifest object earns its keep once\n144\t  multiple producers exist.\n145\t","tool_use_id":"toolu_011stAACzzcp7DeiGs4h3tgF","type":"tool_result"}],"role":"user"},"parentUuid":"229b67ea-f12b-4c4d-b076-b9a302414214","promptId":"6a18c9d5-71db-4940-b513-de12bad67b15","sessionId":"353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","session_id":"353eecbb-eaf7-4854-a575-a9d56e290707","slug":"giggly-dreaming-cookie","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"229b67ea-f12b-4c4d-b076-b9a302414214","timestamp":"2026-07-20T01:52:33.535Z","toolUseResult":{"file":{"content":"# Technical design\n\n**Status:** implemented in v0.1; format may still evolve until v1.\n\n## Scope\n\nConversation Ledger defines a canonical append-only event format plus a local,\ngit-backed storage protocol. It preserves exact visible content while staying\nout of the working tree and syncing only on explicit request.\n\n## Canonical objects\n\nAn `EvidenceEvent` is immutable and has:\n\n- `id`: `ev1-` + sha256 of the event's *identity subset* — the durable,\n  source-determined fields (`kind`, `occurred_at`, `actor.type/id`,\n  `producer.source/session_id`, `conversation`, `media_type`, `content`,\n  `links`). Volatile provenance (`recorded_at`, `context`, `raw`,\n  `producer.tool/version`) is excluded, so re-scanning the same source\n  material always yields the same id: capture is idempotent by construction,\n  and the id doubles as the content hash that makes mutation detectable.\n- `schema` version (`conversation-ledger/v1`);\n- `kind`: `conversation_turn`, `decision`, `document`, `annotation`,\n  `redaction`, or `supersession` — an open string; unknown kinds are stored\n  verbatim so downstream tools can extend without a schema release;\n- `occurred_at` (from the source) and `recorded_at` (at append) timestamps;\n- `actor` (human/agent/system + identity) and `producer` (capture tool,\n  source system, native session id) provenance; adapters stamp human turns\n  with the repo's `git config user.email`/`user.name` (`actor.id`/`.display`)\n  so multi-user clients can filter by author. Because `actor.id` is part of\n  the event identity subset, sessions captured before this stamping existed\n  will produce new event ids if fully re-scanned — the per-session cursor\n  normally prevents that, but a forced rescan can duplicate pre-identity\n  turns;\n- `content`, stored inline, with an optional `media_type`\n  (default `application/json`);\n- `context`: repository identity, branch, `HEAD` SHA, cwd, and a\n  dirty-worktree fingerprint (sha256 of `git status --porcelain`);\n- `conversation`: namespaced id (`claude-code:<session>`) plus a stable\n  `seq` (source line index) providing conversation ordering — the manifest is\n  currently implicit in these fields rather than a separate object;\n- optional `links` (`redacts`, `supersedes`, `annotates`, ...).\n\nConversation turns preserve visible roles, text, tool calls, and tool results\nas supplied by their capture adapter. The source-native payload is retained\nunder `raw` as an opaque, versioned attachment for lossless export.\n\nReasoning policy: record model reasoning when the provider exposes it\n(Claude Code's thinking text is kept, minus opaque signatures); never chase\nit when the provider withholds it (Codex's encrypted `reasoning` payloads\nare skipped, not stored, and never reconstructed).\n\n## Storage\n\nOne git note per **anchor commit** under `refs/notes/conversation-ledger`.\nThe note body is JSONL: one canonical-JSON (sorted-keys) event per line,\nlexicographically sorted, unique.\n\nWhy this shape:\n\n1. **Branch-tied by construction.** Events anchor to `HEAD` at capture time,\n   so conversations ride the commit DAG: merging a branch makes its commits —\n   and therefore their conversations — reachable from the target branch with\n   no sync machinery. `cledger log` scopes to the current branch via\n   `git rev-list` reachability.\n2. **GC-safe, nothing outside git.** All content lives inline in the note\n   blob, reachable from the ref. No orphan data branches, no pointers to\n   stores outside the repository.\n3. **Conflict-free concurrency.** Deterministic serialization + sorted unique\n   lines mean git's `cat_sort_uniq` notes merge strategy (configured per-ref\n   at first append) unions concurrent appends cleanly — the same mechanism\n   git-bug and git-appraise rely on.\n4. **Clean working tree.** Notes never appear in `git status`; sharing is an\n   explicit `cledger sync` (fetch → `git notes merge -s cat_sort_uniq` →\n   push) of that single ref, never implicit.\n\nEvents captured before the first commit exists (unborn `HEAD`) queue in\n`.git/conversation-ledger/pending.jsonl` and flush into the first real\nanchor. Everything under `.git/conversation-ledger/` (pending queue, adapter\ncursors, lock) is local, rebuildable state — never the record of truth.\n\n### Known limitation: squash merges\n\nA squash merge discards the source branch's commits, so their conversations\nremain in the ledger (notes are enumerable regardless of reachability;\n`cledger log --all` sees them) but drop out of the target branch's\nreachability view. A future `re-anchor` operation is the intended fix.\n\n## Capture adapters\n\n`cledger install` registers per-turn hooks globally: Claude Code\n(`Stop`/`SessionEnd` in `~/.claude/settings.json`) and Codex CLI\n(`[[hooks.Stop]]` in `~/.codex/config.toml`). Hooks receive\n`session_id`/`transcript_path`/`cwd` on stdin, no-op silently outside git\nrepositories, never fail the user's session, and re-scan tolerantly —\nidempotent ids make duplicate capture harmless. Per-session cursors under\n`.git/conversation-ledger/cursors/` are a pure optimization.\n\n## Privacy and integrity\n\nVisible tool output can contain secrets. The ledger stays local until an\nexplicit `sync`; retention and remote-sharing policy belong to the repository\nowner. Redaction appends a `redaction` event linking to its target rather\nthan pretending the original never existed; actually purging content is a\ndeliberate, separate operation (planned) since note history retains prior\nblobs. Content hashes (event ids) make accidental mutation detectable.\n\n## Versioning against harness format changes\n\nThree layers exist today:\n\n1. `schema` on every event (`conversation-ledger/v1`) versions the ledger's\n   own envelope.\n2. `raw.format` (`claude-code-jsonl/1`, `codex-rollout-jsonl/1`) versions\n   each adapter's interpretation of its native format; it must be bumped\n   whenever the mapping changes, allowing later reprocessing to know which\n   parser produced an event.\n3. The native payload inside `raw.data` retains the harness's own version\n   markers (Claude Code lines carry `version`; Codex `session_meta` carries\n   `cli_version`), so captured content can always be re-normalized under a\n   newer mapping without recapture.\n\nWhat does not exist yet: drift detection. Adapters are tolerant parsers that\nskip unrecognized line types, which handles additive upstream changes\ngracefully but means a genuinely new message type is dropped entirely (raw\nincluded — only converted lines are stored). See the format-drift roadmap\nitem.\n\n## Open questions\n\n- Secret-safety at capture time: automatic detection/redaction of API keys,\n  tokens, and credentials in tool output before events are written (plus\n  path/pattern-based exclusion rules). Tool output is the highest-risk\n  content in the ledger and currently stored verbatim.\n- Purge tooling for true content removal after redaction.\n- Sub-turn citation anchors for downstream consumers (intent-recall).\n- Re-anchoring after squash merges and history rewrites — ideally default\n  behavior (squash commit inherits its branch's conversations), which\n  requires detecting remote squashes (e.g. GitHub merges) via patch-id or\n  branch-tip matching after fetch.\n- Whether to preserve non-git-controlled harness artifacts that die with a\n  worktree (agent memory directories, session state) as `document` events.\n- Whether an explicit `Conversation` manifest object earns its keep once\n  multiple producers exist.\n","filePath":"/Users/evintunador/repos/evintunador/conversation-ledger/docs/WIP_TECHNICAL_DESIGN.md","numLines":145,"startLine":1,"totalLines":145},"type":"text"},"type":"user","userType":"external","uuid":"8cdeeaba-d645-493f-9ffc-dd612885e08b","version":"2.1.215"},"format":"claude-code-jsonl/1"},"recorded_at":"2026-07-20T01:54:00.054Z","schema":"conversation-ledger/v1"}
{"actor":{"type":"human"},"content":{"blocks":[{"content":"1\t#!/usr/bin/env node\n2\timport { readFileSync } from \"node:fs\";\n3\timport { stdin as input } from \"node:process\";\n4\timport { findRepo, type RepoInfo } from \"./git.js\";\n5\timport {\n6\t  appendEvents,\n7\t  readEvents,\n8\t  sortEvents,\n9\t  sync,\n10\t  type ReadOptions,\n11\t} from \"./store.js\";\n12\timport { parseEventLine, type EventDraft, type EvidenceEvent } from \"./schema.js\";\n13\timport { runClaudeCodeHook, captureClaudeTranscript } from \"./adapters/claude-code.js\";\n14\timport { runCodexHook, captureCodexTranscript } from \"./adapters/codex.js\";\n15\timport { installAdapters } from \"./install.js\";\n16\t\n17\tconst USAGE = `conversation-ledger — durable records of coding-agent conversations, in git notes\n18\t\n19\tUsage:\n20\t  cledger append [--quiet]                 append JSONL events/drafts from stdin\n21\t  cledger log [--all|--rev R] [--kind K] [--source S] [--conversation C] [--json]\n22\t  cledger show <conversation-id-prefix> [--json]\n23\t  cledger conversations [--rev R]         list conversations on current branch (--all for every branch)\n24\t  cledger export [--rev R]                lossless JSONL dump (default: everything)\n25\t  cledger sync [--remote R] [--push|--fetch]   explicit opt-in fetch/merge/push of the ledger ref\n26\t  cledger install <claude-code|codex|all>  hook capture into coding CLIs (global)\n27\t  cledger hook <claude-code>              capture entrypoint invoked by CLI hooks (stdin: hook payload)\n28\t  cledger capture <claude-code|codex> --transcript PATH   manual/backfill ingestion\n29\t  cledger --version | --help\n30\t\n31\tEvents are anchored to the HEAD commit at capture time and stored under\n32\trefs/notes/conversation-ledger, so they follow branches through merges and\n33\tsync only when you say so.`;\n34\t\n35\tfunction version(): string {\n36\t  const pkg = JSON.parse(\n37\t    readFileSync(new URL(\"../package.json\", import.meta.